980","1005":"1005","1027":"1027","1058":"1058","974":"0974","0980":"0980","0954":"0954","0987":"0987","about 1000":"circa 1000","0944":"0944","Ryes, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Falaise, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Française":"Falaise, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Ryes-Bayeux, Normandy, West, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"0980–Abt 1027":"0980–about 1027","0980–1027":"0980–1027","0987–1058":"0987–1058","1000–1062":"1000–1062","1005–1086":"1005–1086","0944–0980":"0944–0980","0954–Female":"0954–Deceased","1000":"1000","Abt 1005":"about 1005","Abt 1027":"about 1027","1086":"1086","1062":"1062","980":"0980","1005":"1005","1027":"1027","1058":"1058","974":"0974","0980":"0980","0954":"0954","0987":"0987","about 1000":"about 1000","0944":"0944","Ryes, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Falaise, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Française":"Falaise, Calvados, Normandy, France","Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Ryes-Bayeux, Normandy, West, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France","Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France":"Ryes, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Rea  .","English: topographic name for someone living at a place where rye (Old English <i>ryge</i>) was grown, or perhaps an occupational name for someone who grew or sold it.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads so named, most of them from Old Norse <i>rjóthr</i> ‘clearing in a forest’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ryer","meanings":["English (Sussex and Kent): probably from   Rye   (see   Rea  ) + the suffix <i>-er</i>, and is thus synonymous with Middle English <i>atte Rye</i>, denoting someone who lived by a river or an island. This type of formation is common in Sussex and Kent.","Americanized form of German   Reier   ‘heron’ or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rajar</b> or <b>Rajer</b> (see   Rayer  )."]},{"name":"Romney","meanings":["English: habitational name from Romney (Kent), from an uncertain first element (perhaps an Old English personal name <i>Rūmen</i>) + Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river, stream’. Compare   Rye   2."]},{"name":"Rea","meanings":["English: from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter ye</i> ‘at the island’ (Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on an island or patch of firm ground surrounded by marsh, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rye (Sussex), The Rye in High Wycombe (Buckinghamshire), Rye Hill in Epping Upland (Essex), Rye Mill in Feering (Essex), and Rye House in Stanstead Abbots (Hertfordshire). Alternatively, the name may also arise from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter eye</i> ‘at the river’ (Old English <i>ēa</i>) and may also be topographic, for someone who lived near a river or stream, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rea in Hempsted (Gloucestershire), Ray Lodge in Lingfield (Surrey), and Rye Farm in Cranleigh (Surrey). Due to the similarity of Middle English forms it is now impossible to distinguish between the two explanations. See also   Nye  .","English: post-medieval form of   Wray  .","English: variant of   Ray  ."]}]},{"name":"Eudes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Eade  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Eads","meanings":["and Norwegian equivalent of <b>Matthew</b> ."]},{"name":"Eade","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which originated as a nickname from a word denoting something round and lumpish. It is one of several given names that owe their origin to their use for a character in  Margaret Mitchell's  novel Gone with the Wind (  1936 )."]},{"name":"Edes","meanings":["This name is found as a variant or pet form of   Edith   in Yorkshire from the 15th century onwards. It is recorded as a baptismal name in the 16th century. In present-day use it probably refers to the biblical ‘Garden of Eden’, crew ῾<i>eden</i> ‘place of pleasure’. As a boy's name it may also represent a variant of   Aidan   or a transferred use of a surname, itself derived in the Middle Ages from a given name <i>Edun</i> or <i>Edon</i>. This is of Old English origin, from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’."]},{"name":"Edds","meanings":["Pet form of any of several old German names beginning with <i>Ed-</i>. The Elder and Younger <i>Eddas</i> are also the names of two influential Old Icelandic books of Norse myths and poems."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eudes de Rye was born in 0980, in Ryes, Calvados, Normandy, France, his father, Geiffrey de Rye, was 36 and his mother, Mrs. De Reys, was 26. He had at least 2 sons with Albreda Harcourt de Villes de Beaumont. H